# Skipr browser extension

## Layout

- `skipr-plugin/` is the single loadable extension root for **Firefox and Chrome** — no per-browser forks.
- `ext.js` is the only place for `browser` / `chrome` branching; other files call `getStorage()`.
- `config.js` holds `DEFAULT_API_BASE` and `resolveApiUrl()` — load after `ext.js` in manifest and popup.
- Do not add build tooling or repo docs inside `skipr-plugin/` unless the extension needs them at runtime.

## Cross-browser APIs

```javascript
// ext.js — do not duplicate this pattern elsewhere
const ext = typeof globalThis.browser !== "undefined" ? globalThis.browser : globalThis.chrome;
```

Load `ext.js` before `processor.js` (manifest `content_scripts`) and before `popup.js` (popup.html).

## Manifest (MV3)

- `manifest_version: 3`; toolbar UI uses `action`, not `browser_action`.
- API fetch permission lives in `host_permissions`; `storage` stays in `permissions`.
- Bump `version` for any user-facing release.
- `browser_specific_settings.gecko` is Firefox-only (add-on ID); Chrome ignores it.
- `background.js` sets toolbar badge colors: green (Active/ready), yellow (Pending), red (Failed); clears on idle.
- Content scripts only run on `https://www.youtube.com/watch*` — broaden matches deliberately.

## Content script (`processor.js`)

- Resolves API base via `resolveApiUrl(storage.server)` — custom override when set, else `DEFAULT_API_BASE` from `config.js`; appends `/api/v2/timestamps`.
- API `fetch` runs in `background.js` (`fetch-timestamps` message) — not from the content script; avoids Chrome Private Network Access blocking localhost from `youtube.com`.
- Detects SPA navigation via History API hooks + URL polling — preserve this when refactoring video-change detection.
- Skip check uses throttled `timeupdate` on the active `<video>` (250ms); clear listeners in `stopTracking()` before re-attaching on video change.
- Skip toasts live in `notifications.js`; level stored as `notifyLevel` (`off` | `minimal` | `detailed`).
- `skippingEnabled` (default `true`) in `storage.sync` gates `checkAndSkip`; badge shows gray **Paused** when off but intervals are loaded.
- API returns `pending` (HTTP 202), `ready` with `intervals` (HTTP 200), or `failed` with `error` — poll every 3s only while pending; log failures, do not poll.
- Manual retry: popup **Try again** → `retry-analysis` message → `GET` with `retry=1` once; subsequent pending polls omit `retry`.
- Validate ready responses with `parseIntervals()`; cancel polls and ignore stale fetches via `fetchGeneration` + `video_ref`.

## Popup (`popup.js` / `popup.html`)

- Default API is `DEFAULT_API_BASE` in `config.js`; optional override saved to `storage.sync` key `server` (blank = default).
- Server override lives under collapsed **Advanced** (`<details>`); main popup stays install-and-go.
- Register event listeners once (inside `DOMContentLoaded`).

## Testing checklist

1. Reload unpacked extension in **Firefox and Chrome** after any `skipr-plugin/` change.
2. Refresh open YouTube tabs (content scripts do not hot-reload).
3. Set server URL in popup → confirm `storage.sync` persists across browser restart.
4. Open a watch URL → verify GET to `/api/v2/timestamps?link=...` in Network tab.
5. With known timestamps, confirm playback jumps past `start_time`–`end_time` ranges.
6. Navigate to another video without full page reload → confirm new timestamps are fetched.

## Scope discipline

- Minimal diffs; no frameworks or bundlers unless the project outgrows vanilla JS.
- Keep console prefix `[Skipr]` consistent unless renaming project-wide.
